name: Terry Alldredge
text:
David Phelps & The Martins
Apr. 12, 2019

Outstanding performances!

Will not go back to:

Clearbranch United Methodist Church
8051 Glenn Road
Trussville, AL 35173 US

1. Tickets and program said doors open at 6pm. Got there at 5:45 and parking lot was full of cars but no people. The doors had been opened for some time and the place was already full. Although there isn't really a bad seat in the house, there were certainly no choices.

2. Seat savers. There were empty seats sprinkled throughout the venue. 2, 4 seats saved was common. Did see a line of 6 seats that were being saved. We were continually waved off by the seat savers. I suspect that is a result of rude, selfish church members. I don't care about the money but General Admission is first come first served and this was rude. Above and beyond rude.

3. A group of 3 church members were next to us. The one by my wife had the nerve to ask her to stop singing. To stop singing, rudely! My wife is an excellent gospel singer herself and she wasn't singing loudly by any means. Of course, most of the audience was singing with every song. After their confrontation (it was a continuation because my wife isn't a push over for rude people) the woman commenced to belting as loudly as she wanted and so did her friends. (Although it doesn't matter, they were not good singers.)

The atmosphere was overall wonderful due to the Spirit moving through the performers. The church members need their culture changed. They're selfish and rude. Won't be back to that venue..

Terry Alldredge

Follow up on your follow up - I appreciate that you've responded however you've gone considerable lengths to avoid any responsibility. It figures... The rude lady identified herself as a member and stated she and her 2 friends were a 'singing group' there.

There is just simply no way that the number of people allowed inside before the posted door opening time had purchased VIP tickets. The place was at least 95% full.

I'm sure you're a Spirit filled church and that you do good work for the Lord. It is apparent that this issue doesn't really phase you.

Again, won't be back...

resp.text:
Terry,
Thank you so much for coming to the event at Clearbranch!  We are sorry you had some issues, but hope that your evening was an overall good one.  Keep in mind that this was not a Clearbranch Ministry event, but instead a national tour where we served as the venue.
As for your point about admission, general admission was let in at 6pm.  There were a number of people that purchased the VIP package offered by the promotion company.  This allowed them early entry.
For the point about seat savers, we are sorry.  This is not behavior we normally see so we have to say that we are surprised.  Keep in mind that there were a large number of people here that evening that were not Clearbranch members.
We are so sorry that your wife had a bad experience with the people sitting beside you.  Did these people identify them selves as Clearbranch members?  We ask because, once again, this is not typical behavior that we see.
Overall Terry, we are sorry that you had a negative experience, but hope that you did get to enjoy the concert and that the evening was a blessing to you.  Have a fantastic Easter and please call our church office if there is something else we can help you with.

Mark Harvard
Director of Communications
Clearbranch UMC

text:
I was raised as a Baptist. My daddy was a preacher and preached at several small Baptist Churches in the Wetumpka area.

I enjoyed the small church atmosphere. When I recently moved back to Wetumpka, my first visit was to the First United Methodist Church of Wetumpka. All the people were great and welcoming.

Even though, I would not say FUMC is small, it has the small church attitude. Friendly people, and a great Minister, Matt Albritton. I was impressed with his friendly, down to earth personality. If he ever meets you once, don't be surprised if the next time he sees you he will call you by name!

name: Christina Barnett
text:
In my search for a preschool for my first born, I did A LOT of research. I toured almost every preschool in Madison County. It became almost an obsession. I wanted the BEST school for my daughter (even though she's only 2), as I'm sure all mothers do.  One where I knew she'd be safe. One where I knew she'd be taught and learn things. One where the teachers actually cared about her well being. One where they would work with me and keep me involved in everything. One that wouldn't break the bank.

When I found the Preschool Program at MUMC, it seemed to check all of my boxes. My sweet girl has been attending for several months now and I can say confidently this Preschool Program is absolutely wonderful and everything I ever dreamed for her. My daughter loves going to "school" here. Her teachers seem like they truly care about their work and my daughter (shout out to Ms. Angela and Ms. Cheryl). It's not just a babysitting gig - they actually have a curriculum, structure, discipline, and my girl comes home just gabbing about all of the things she's learned and all the fun she had with her "friends." The Director, Ms. Krista, is very kind, welcoming, and really seems to enjoy her job - she's also very organized and is a great communicator with us parents, which I really appreciate. The teachers and Ms. Krista all gave me wonderful guidance and instruction on how to potty train my daughter (I was very nervous because I'd never potty trained a kid before) and after just one weekend, she was potty trained - they've been really helpful with staying consistent at school, support what I do at home, and have been willing to work together with me on anything I've asked for. I feel that my daughter is well taken care of, and actually being challenged and taught things. The tuition isn't unreasonable and actually cheaper than some of those stand alone premium preschools that aren't tied to a church. Everyone is upbeat and full of joy here.  I highly recommend this Preschool Program to anyone!

text: I'm not really a church goer these days, but I still have a lot of love and respect for this church.  They've always struck me as genuinely charitable.  I've been to a few different churches in the area and so many of them seem kind of greedy, using their tithes mostly for growth instead of helping others (at least not on the scale that I'd expect of a church).  Good Shepherd is always ready to help people in need, whether it's through the food pantry, storm shelter, mission trips, or hurricane-relief type trips.  United Methodists really are very accepting and kind in my opinion.  I recommend this if you're the church type that shies away from the hellfire and brimstone kind of places.  It's a very calm kind of church.  Not overwhelming in the slightest.

name: Nancy Bangel
text: Good Shepherd UMC is a good choice for those who are interested in mission outreach, especially within the community. With a Red Cross storm shelter, Upward basketball, a build group that will build wheelchair ramps upon request, tornado relief, prison ministry, preK/K program, and more, they are a very active congregation. One thing that drew us to this church was the fact that the church is so active it is open much more than just on Sunday morning. It has contemporary music which meets our needs but may not be for everyone.

text: This iconic church is a service driven organization.  The day care is one of the very best, with loving competent staff and every precaution taken to maintain the health and safety of the children.  We have loved our association with the day care and the church as a whole.

name: Hannah S
text:
My 2 year old attends daycare here and it is phenomenal! Everyone is friendly, patient, and know how to handle kids. My daughter gets so excited every time we pull up in the parking lot. Classrooms are huge for all ages and there's also an art room, a playground, a gymnasium, a large formal hall with stage, and a chapel. The church services and study classes are also great. Nobody is judgemental and I do not get that fake super happy churchy vibe from anyone like I have at just about every other one I've been to.
There's a good mix of kids, teens, young adults, middle age, and seniors. I highly recommend.
